  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">2017 2018 Single grant: South Sudan Crisis - Response in Uganda</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Enhanced food security and livelihoods through food production and non-agricultural income generation in and around the Bidibidi Refugee Settlement</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">South Sudan has been war-torn by civil strife since 2013 following the failed coup attempt by Riek Machar. In July 2016, violent conflict escalated drastically, leading to massive forced displacements and disrupted agricultural activities. This in combination with drought has exhausted many families&#x2019; means of survival, bringing South Sudan into an acute food crisis. Famine was formally declared in February 2017 by the UN adding to the mass influx of South Sudanese refugees into the neighbouring countries. The average daily influx of South Sudanese refugees into Uganda has since July 2016 been approx. 2,100 refugees , peaking in February 2017 with about 6,700 daily new arrivals. Through Caritas Uganda, Caritas Denmark supports Caritas Aruas livelihood aid to South Sudanese refugees in zone 4 of the Bidibidi Refugee Settlement in Northern Uganda. The project includes both a conflict prevention component, environmental protection, and in line with national legislation commits 30% to the host communities.</narrative>
  </description>
